@realDonaldTrump Tuesday’s proceedings showed us the best and the worst in man. Jim Jordan and Devin Nunes continue to disgrace Congress by their mere presence in the institution. John Bolton is a coward for allowing his subordinates to testify—including Fiona Hill,

Tim Morrison, and Colonel Vindman—while he hides behind a court proceeding, hoping to avoid testimony so that his $2 million book deal can boast of “Never before revealed facts about Trump’s corruption!” It would be nice if Bolton would put country over money and tell us now

what information he knows that is relevant to the impeachment inquiry. Nonetheless, we should be heartened that it takes only a handful of honest men and women to expose the truth and hold a president accountable. Although dozens of administration officials knew of

Trump’s bribery and said nothing, one whistleblower made all the difference. The McCarthy Era ended when Joseph Welch, Chief Counsel for the Army, said to McCarthy at a public hearing, “Have you no sense of decency, sir?” Colonel Vinman’s statement that
